    <term>Step 3: Data Analysis:</term> In the <term>Analysis</term> section of the article, the researchers describe which statistical inference methods were used to analyze the data, and the results of the data analyses are provided in the <term>Results</term> section of the article.


    "To examine that, we utilized a one-way analysis of variance (ANOVA) using three levels of the variable Group (caffeine, nap, placebo), separately for recall and recognition. 
    Significant ANOVAs were followed-up by examining differences between groups at the specific time point with independent samples t-tests."

    "Recall memory for Word List 1 after 7 h retention interval showed significant group differences (F = 5.41 p = 0.009, partial eta2 = 0.25, Fig. 2a). Post hoc tests showed: (a) the nap group performed significantly better than the caffeine group (p = 0.003); (b) nap performed marginally better than placebo (p = 0.06.); and (c) there were non-significant differences between caffeine and placebo (p = 0.22). Recognition memory for words after a 7 h retention interval also showed significant group differences for dâ€™ (F = 4.51 p = 0.019, partial eta2 = 0.22, Fig. 2b). Post hoc tests showed: (a) nap performed significantly better than caffeine (p = 0.008); (b) nap better than placebo (p = 0.03); and (c) no difference between caffeine and placebo (p = 0.50)."

</p>



<p>
    <term>Step 4: Draw Conclusions from the Data:</term> In the <term>Discussion</term> section of the article, the researchers state their overall conclusions obtained during Steps 2 and 3. Conclusions are written in the context of the entire investigation and in relationship to findings from previous studies. Conclusions are applied more boradly (beyond the subjects in the study), and researchers conclude that napping directly <term>causes</term> the higher recall ability. They state <q>...naps improved the ability to learn a new list of words ...</q>. 
</p>

<note>
    <p>Studies must be designed in a specific way in order to draw cause-and-effect conclusions!</p>
</note>
